AeroDuel ‚Äì ESP32 Firmware

Firmware for the AeroDuel RC planes using an ESP32 Dev Module.
This project uses PlatformIO + Arduino framework.

üì¶ 1. Requirements

Make sure you have:

Visual Studio Code

PlatformIO extension for VS Code

USB cable for ESP32

ESP32 Dev Module (example: Espressif ESP32 Dev Module)

You do not need to install Arduino IDE or toolchains manually ‚Äî PlatformIO handles that automatically.

Project Setup

Open VS Code

Install PlatformIO IDE extension (if you haven‚Äôt already)

Click PlatformIO Home ‚Üí New Project

Use the following settings:

Project Name: (anything you want)

Board: Espressif ESP32 Dev Module

Framework: Arduino

Click Create Project

This generates the standard PlatformIO folder structure: /src
/include
/lib
platformio.ini

‚öôÔ∏è platformio.ini Configuration

Replace your platformio.ini with:
[env:esp32dev]
platform = espressif32
board = esp32dev
framework = arduino
monitor_speed = 115200

lib_deps =
    sandeepmistry/LoRa@^0.8.0

upload_port = COM6

Change COM6 to whatever COM port your ESP32 is using.

Installing Dependencies

PlatformIO installs libs automatically, but run this to force-update them: Installing Dependencies

PlatformIO installs libs automatically, but run this to force-update them: pio pkg update

To rebuild everything clean:
pio run -t clean

Normal Upload

If your ESP32 uploads normally, just run: pio run -t upload

If your board requires manual boot mode

Some ESP32 Dev Modules require holding buttons during upload.

Buttons

EN (Enable/Reset): Restarts the board

BOOT / IO0: Puts the ESP32 into firmware upload mode

To Upload Manually

Hold BOOT / IO0
Run: pio run -t upload

Keep holding BOOT until you see:
connecting.............

Then just let go of button.

Resetting the Board

To reset the board at any time:

Tap the EN button

This restarts the ESP32 without entering upload mode.

Serial Monitor

To open serial monitor at 115200 baud:
pio device monitor

To exit Press: CTRL+C